We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:

The Municipal Accountant to properly classify procurement of supplies or materials for distribution to the appropriate inventory items and recognize the corresponding expenses only upon actual distribution;

The MGSO is requested to:

Issue the inventory items only to end users/actual recipients;

Provide the distribution list of recipients to support the RIS attached to the DV as submitted; and

Provide the Accounting Unit with the inventory of undistributed sets of routers as a basis for the recognition of inventory, if any.

Create an Inventory/Inspection Committee through an administrative order for purposes of the following:

Regularly inspect the deliveries of the Municipality;

Conduct physical count of inventories semestrally; 

Prepare and submit the RPCI to the Accounting Office and GSO for reconciliation, copy furnish to COA;

The MGSO:

Upon receipt of the delivery receipts and/or sales invoice for the goods delivered, prepare AIR and submit to the Municipal Accountant;

Upon issuance of goods to the end-users, prepare RIS, summarize the issuances, prepare RSMI, and submit the RSMI together with the RIS to the Municipal Accountant; and

Maintain and regularly update stock cards of inventories;

The Municipal Accountant:

Upon receipt of the AIR and its supporting documents, draw a JEV to recognize inventory and accounts payable in the books;

Upon receipt of SSMI and its supporting documents such as RIS and/or Distribution List, draw a JEV to recognize the issuance of inventories to expense; and

Maintain and regularly update the supplies ledger cards.

The BAC is to:

Ensure that all procurements shall be done through competitive bidding unless the use of alternative methods of procurement is applicable in highly exceptional cases; 

Procurement of goods through emergency cases shall be made only in exceptional cases and in strict compliance with the conditions for the use of negotiated procurement through emergency cases;


The Hospital Administrator to:

Implement effective inventory management system to forecast and procure in advance the needs for drugs and medicines; 

During budget call, submit PPMP to the Municipal Budget Office and as basis for the preparation of the APP by the BAC in the ensuing year that will guide the procurement activities to be undertaken in the ensuing year; and

All procurement undertaken shall be included in the approved APP of the Municipality unless duly justified by the BAC through its resolution.

We reiterated our recommendation for the Accounting Office:

To complete the preparation of the reconciliation report of the reciprocal accounts Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds in the three funds (GF, SF & TF);

To take up the necessary adjustment in the books of accounts of the respective funds upon completion of the reconciliation;

The Municipal Mayor to:

Direct the Municipal Engineering Office to prepare and maintain a monthly monitoring report to keep track of the progress of all PPAs especially those that involved infrastructure projects within its jurisdiction from planning to its completion stage;

Assign Project Heads/Managers to all non-infrastructure PPAs to prepare and consolidate a Monthly Monitoring Report;

Direct the Municipal Engineering Office and the assigned Project Heads/Managers to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant on the costs incurred in each PPAs as basis in the preparation of their Monthly Monitoring Report which should be submitted to COA at least on a quarterly basis; and

Require the Municipal Engineering Office and the assigned Project Heads/Manager to strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the LCE institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment; 
to identify critical processes and functions; 
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review,  to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management should improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

The Municipal Mayor to require:

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain PPELC and property cards, respectively, and update the same regularly;


The Municipal Accountant to make a detailed review and reconciliation of the PPE accounts specially with those accounts with unreconciled balances to determine its cause/s and record the necessary adjustments or corrections in the books of the Municipality.

a. The MGSO to:

Ensure that the RIS and RSMI are properly filled up and with complete signatures. For drugs and medicines, a certification from the hospital or the RHU that such items were issued to patients attached to the RSMI;

Submit monthly RSMI together with the RIS and hospital certifications to the Municipal Accountant;

b. The Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare a JEV to adjust the erroneous entry made;

Strengthen review of JEV before posting in the books of accounts;

Stop the practice of using the ending inventory of various end users as basis for recording the expenses; and

Record the expenses based on the RSMI submitted by the MGSO, moving forward.

