We recommended that:








The LGU to maintain a separate Trust Fund for collections received from the 20% share of building permit fees and other charges;

The Municipal Treasurer's Office to segregate their collections in the Abstract of Collection into 80% accruing to the General Fund, 15% held in trust for OBO operations, and, 5% share of the DPWH Secretary which shall be remitted thru the Bureau of Treasury;  

Using the abstract as basis of recording, the Accounting Department to also record 80% of the collection as income under the General Fund, the 15% as Trust Liability under the Trust Fund books, and the 5% as Due to National Government Agencies (Due to NGAs).

The program coordinator of the livelihood project to draft a properly documented comprehensive guidelines emphasizing the process of orientation, eligibility requirements and its evaluation, modalities of assistance and release cycle, repayment scheme and monitoring of program implementation for the approval of the Municipality;

Consider the revision of the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) in the succeeding releases to indicate the mode of payment whether installment or lump sum and indicate penalty clause in case of default; and

Issue demand letter to women's associations which already defaulted its payment beyond the term indicated in the MOA.

1.    We recommended that the municipality’s GAD Focal Point System to conduct gender mainstreaming through gender audit and gender analysis of its policies, programs, services and the current situation of the municipality in terms of GAD compliance;

2.    To equip the GFPS with the in-depth knowledge and capacity on GAD, it also recommended that they to undergo trainings and seminars such as those relating to gender-responsive planning and budgeting, gender analysis, gender audit and the use of various GAD tools for the LGU’s GAD implementation of PAPs; and

3.    Revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9710 and other provisions of law relating to GAD.

We recommended that Management should:

a.    Create a team to immediately and without delay, conduct a thorough investigation and analysis of prior years’ transactions in order to establish the causes of the discrepancy, which could be errors in recording and/or cash shortage of the accountable officers;

b.    Direct concerned officers and employees of the Treasury and Accounting Offices to exercise prudence in recording financial transactions and perform reconciliation procedures on a periodic basis to prevent the accumulation of unreconciled balances; 

c.    Ensure that proper review of recorded transactions is done by concerned officers of the Accounting Unit as a deterrent to errors and irregularities; and

d.    Direct the Municipal Treasurer whose official leave had already expired to report back to office and render her accounts and turn-over her cash and property accountabilities to the incoming Treasurer. Should she still fail, inform the Bureau of Local Government Finance of the situation and recommend for the creation of a committee subject to BLGF regulations, or create a committee to force-open her vault and other cash receptacles in the presence of personnel from the BLGF and Provincial Treasurer’s Office, together with the representative of the Mayor’s Office and the previous Municipal Treasurer’s immediate family to be witnessed by COA for the proper transfer and inventory of cash and property under her care.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommend that:

A. There should be a timely submission of cash advance voucher and its supporting documents to the COA Audit Team Leader by the Municipal Accountant or any authorized representative which shall not exceed seven days from the release of check in accordance with Section 6.1.8.4;

B. The Municipal Accountant should stop the granting of cash advance for CF equivalent to one year and limit the granting to only three months or monthly, whichever is more applicable to the LGU in accordance with Section 6.1.5;

C. The HoA being the SDO should stop drawing cash advance more than the maximum cash accountability as stated in the approved bond application in accordance with Section 6.1.3; and

D. After liquidation of cash advance, a copy of the transmittal letter duly received by the ICFAU should be forwarded to the COA ATL concerned. Responsibilities of the Agency Accountant and the HoA on the granting and liquidation of CF should be religiously adhered to and should be in accordance with the provisions of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 and other applicable laws.

